column7: i looked carefully at the path created by the blinking lights , it was quite challenging . my strategy was to click each node once and follow the path. i did not see any errors or bugs
i followed the speed of the flashing yellow circles to figure out which connections went where, i found it difficult as you had to concentrate very hard

I found this quite hard, partly because of the delay so you didn't know which connector had set off what, partly because of the speed and partly because of needing to figure out if they were going both ways or not. I tried to work it out by going through each connector and isolating what they did, and if they overlapped with others.
This problem was hard for me and I would enjoy trying this again
I tried to just notice any procedural advancements in the lights. I thought that indicated a flow of current. But it seems that was not always true.
tried to follow the yellow. it was hard. i didnt spot any bugs,
Trial and Error
When the yellow lights appeared. I found it difficult to understand completely how the connection worked. I noticed that some of the yellow lights went crazy and kept flashing.

I just clicked the button and clicked the directions that the button lighted up from button to button. I found it hard when the buttons lighted up fast and kept repeating themselves in a random pattern without stopping and when two buttons lighted up at the same time. Im not sure if it was a bug or it was meant to be like that but after clicking confirm I was able to click the buttons and I might have been able to change the grey areas (I didn't try so I'm not sure)
its was hard
Followed the direction of the lights, kind of animating their movement in my head. Wasn't too hard, once I had the hang of it.
It was very hard, I had no idea what was going on!

i found it difficult at first to follow the points but as the trial went on i noticed moving the arrows i could track the points.  was also difficult when selecting multiple points when it kept changing.
Didnt find errors or bugs. To find where the connections were, I just went with some of the connections that I saw in the examples. Some were correct.

I went around the diagram clicking the circles in a clockwise motion, giving each one time to play out its sequence. This is how I figured out which did what and could more easily out where the connections may be. It seemed to have worked in most cases and I feel quite accomplished. I really enjoyed this task, there was definitely an element of difficulty involved and I felt good when I got correct answers. There were no errors on my end :-)
i found it a hard process overall
Followed the direction of the flashing yellow circle.

Initially, despite reading the instructions carefully I wasn't sure exactly what was required. It wasn't until around the 5th test that I fully understood what was required. The strategy was clicking on each node and following where it went, indicating the direction. It was more difficult when bi directional nodes were active.
I just went one at a time and tried to follow the directions. I found it difficult when there was many different lights to follow and when they were fast.
It was somewhat difficult, because of the delays. I do not think there were bugs or errors but it was hard to tell. My strategy was just to follow the lights and see the sequence they lit up in.

It took me a while to get used to what was going on and how to get it, but once I got the hang of it I could see it more clearly. So was quite confusing to begin with. I just mentally note which connections worked for each circle I clicked.
I found that with the ones that had two way connections, the signal kept going so it was almost impossible to run more tests because the last one hadn't stopped

I waited to see the lights flash and imagined the connections that must exist and which way the current would flow. Sometimes when there could have been two possible connections that caused a light to flash, I found it difficult to choose which connection was correct, though I'm sure there was a process of elimination way to figure it out. The only error I spotted was, it said there were 0 trials left when there were still trials left.
Followed the lights, it was pretty easy
I found the instructions quite heavy and not overly clear, I think a more interactive sample would have been preferred.
followed the circles that lit up, it got easier as a followed the patterns. Delayed more often than I expected.

I just watched, clicked on a circle and waited till the connections stopped firing, then moved onto the next one. Sometimes I accidentally clicked on a circle before the last one stopped firing and it messed everything up. Also sometimes I was 100% sure I got the connections right but then they were wrong somehow. Found it relatively easy. The only bug (though i'm not sure if a bug) I encountered was sometimes the connections didn't even stop firing.

I clicked on each marker and marked on all connections it made, then altered these when I clicked on other makers to reflect the patterns. I found it difficult to start with but felt I got the hang of things as the experiment progressed.
I found them hard because I couldn't work out how it worked
I tried to find patterns at individual connections, then verified them via the other connections. The four node ones were harder, both due to the shape and the limited guesses. No bugs/errors.

it took me a while to realise that to confirm the connections you have to click the actual links between the two. i didn't think the test represented the connections properly either as some of the ones shown to me as wrong looked right when i was doing it but perhaps thats the nature of the test. my strategy really was just to watch what lit upa fter i clicked one of the circles.

I had some difficulty figuring out the connections and wasn't really sure of how to figure them out, even after reading the instructions and seeing the example. I didn't have a strategy. No bugs or errors found.
